<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-07-31T18:02:14-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-07-31T18:02:14-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6724&amp;p=65269#p65269</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6724&amp;p=65269#p65269"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Mapper 0 Games that use 8x16 sprites?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6724&amp;p=65269#p65269"><![CDATA[
In 8x16 pixel mode:<br /><br />OAM tile number $14 -&gt; $0140 and $0150<br />OAM tile number $15 -&gt; $1140 and $1150<br />OAM tile number $16 -&gt; $0160 and $0170<br />OAM tile number $17 -&gt; $1160 and $1170<br /><br />It's convenient that the base of the hexadecimal number system commonly used for VRAM addresses is the same as the length of one tile in bytes.<br /><br />Lode Runner has an "edit mode" with 8x16 pixel sprites and no scrolling. It was the first 8x16 game I ever encountered.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Jul 31, 2010 6:02 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
